00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:12.110
DAN GALPIN: Yes.

00:12:12.110 --> 00:12:13.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: That was
a good sorting game.

00:12:13.720 --> 00:12:15.890
This game--

00:12:15.890 --> 00:12:19.020
I mean, maybe if you're three.

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:20.890
DAN GALPIN: Well, and I'll say
some other things to note.

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:24.420
You can see that there is a
real, real problem with this

00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:25.765
particular screen size
and resolution.

00:12:25.765 --> 00:12:28.052
And you can see the retry button
and the quit button are

00:12:28.052 --> 00:12:29.020
really squashed.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:30.000
And this actually goes--

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.010
do we even have--

00:12:31.010 --> 00:12:32.885
IAN NI-LEWIS: To be fair, this
system's an easy resolution.

00:12:32.885 --> 00:12:36.180
It's not a common
aspect ratio.

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:38.190
DAN GALPIN: It's just the
resolution used by every

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.320
single Android tablet
out there.

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:40.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, no.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:41.390
This isn't.

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:42.550
DAN GALPIN: Oh, yeah.

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:43.710
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's
in HDMI mode.

00:12:43.710 --> 00:12:44.130
DAN GALPIN: Excuse me, yeah.

00:12:44.130 --> 00:12:46.730
But even outside of HDMI mode,
it's still squashed.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:49.550
IAN NI-LEWIS: So what I'm
saying, though, is that yeah,

00:12:49.550 --> 00:12:51.690
the particular aspect ratio
that we're looking at is

00:12:51.690 --> 00:12:54.020
extremely squashed because we're
in HDMI mode, and it's a

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:54.750
little bit weird.

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:56.620
DAN GALPIN: But let me point
one thing out there.

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:57.310
Sorry, go on.

00:12:57.310 --> 00:12:59.880
So this is actually
their listing.

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.490
And the listing also has a
completely squashed and

00:13:02.490 --> 00:13:05.030
different aspect ratio
from the actual game.

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:09.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, but my point
really is that phones

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.420
are getting longer.

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:14.570
Aspect ratios change.

00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:18.540
There is no device on the market
that I'm aware of that

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:22.060
will guarantee always being
the same forever.

00:13:22.060 --> 00:13:25.860
With Android, the nice thing is
that at least we've thought

00:13:25.860 --> 00:13:32.060
about that and gone through
the pain so that you can--

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:33.170
we have a new rule, right?

00:13:33.170 --> 00:13:35.750
No static slides for more
than five seconds.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.540
DAN GALPIN: So let's go back.

00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:39.460
I just wanted to show that
because it was sort of

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:39.530
entertaining.

00:13:39.530 --> 00:13:43.650
And I did want to actually
mention that this is also not

00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:47.110
a particularly good
listing page.

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:49.170
But it is representative
of the game, at

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:49.910
least, which is good.

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:52.090
There's a lot of listings
that aren't.

00:13:52.090 --> 00:13:54.030
IAN NI-LEWIS: Anyway, to be
fair, I guess what I was

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:57.180
trying to say is, Android gives
you the tools to deal

00:13:57.180 --> 00:13:58.905
with these aspect
ratio changes.

00:13:58.905 --> 00:14:00.920
And especially when you're doing
vector graphics, there

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:04.350
really shouldn't be any reason
to make these mistakes.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:05.490
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:14:05.490 --> 00:14:06.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now I've
said my piece.

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:07.300
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, that's good.

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:09.310
IAN NI-LEWIS: Dan, I'm
going to shut up now.

