IAN NI-LEWIS: How can we
not play with beer?

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:22.150
Have you tried this game?

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.550
Don't do it in a dry county,
that's all I'm saying.

00:14:29.550 --> 00:14:31.020
DAN GALPIN: All right, well,
I think that pretty

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:33.110
much says it all.

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:35.340
I mean, there's some
good ideas here.

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:37.710
It definitely needs to
feel more fluid.

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:42.390
My basic complaint with this
game, and I think part of it

00:14:42.390 --> 00:14:44.980
is the aspect ratio, I think it
is having trouble dealing

00:14:44.980 --> 00:14:47.840
with touches and with handling
the characters on this

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:49.700
particular screen.

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:52.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: And also, when
you're doing a sorting game

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:53.830
like this--

00:14:53.830 --> 00:14:55.060
and I'll tell you what the main

00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:56.450
problem is with the mechanics.

00:14:56.450 --> 00:14:58.230
Let's talk about the things
they did right.

00:14:58.230 --> 00:14:59.430
They did vector graphics.

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:01.570
And the vector graphics look
really, really good.

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:02.660
So those turned out well.

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:03.990
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:15:03.990 --> 00:15:06.100
I think they're high-res
Illustrator graphics that have

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:07.170
been rendered.

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:08.720
I don't think they're actually
vector here.

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:10.570
I think they've just been
rendered into bitmaps.

00:15:10.570 --> 00:15:12.780
IAN NI-LEWIS: Quite possible.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:16.140
The basic game idea, there's
nothing wrong with it.

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:19.205
I would say the interaction
is a little difficult.

00:15:19.205 --> 00:15:22.310
A sorting game like this, you
probably want to have a little

00:15:22.310 --> 00:15:26.000
bit of momentum physics so that
it doesn't turn into a

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.590
laborious dragging game where
you're fighting the interface

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:30.580
more than you're fighting
the game.

00:15:30.580 --> 00:15:31.650
DAN GALPIN: And I was going to
say, on a phone it's not so

00:15:31.650 --> 00:15:33.380
bad because you don't
have to drag as far.

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:35.530
But as soon as you get to a
tablet, if you don't actually

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:38.150
have the physics built into it,
then you really are just,

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:39.840
oh, I'm dragging this
thing across the

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:40.720
screen again and again.

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:42.940
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, and you saw
many times Dan made this

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:43.510
same mistake.

00:15:43.510 --> 00:15:46.820
You let go just a fraction
of a second too early.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:50.920
And instead of getting in and
giving you points, you just

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:51.540
hit a bug, basically.

00:15:51.540 --> 00:15:52.840
DAN GALPIN: It floats
to the top.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:54.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: The guy just
sits on top of the train

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:56.590
looking weird.

00:15:56.590 --> 00:15:58.490
It's really great when the train
then takes off and runs

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:00.710
them all over, by the way,
which it does do.

00:16:00.710 --> 00:16:02.620
But there's no running
over [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:03.710
IAN NI-LEWIS: I guess, yeah.

00:16:03.710 --> 00:16:05.130
It's kind of fun.

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:08.710
Anyway, this is some great
programming, no

00:16:08.710 --> 00:16:09.360
question about it.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:10.855
It's just, it's not finished.

00:16:10.855 --> 00:16:12.010
It's not a finished game.

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:13.770
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it
needs more work.

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:14.110
IAN NI-LEWIS: All right.

00:16:14.110 --> 00:16:14.800
Let's move on.

00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:15.230
DAN GALPIN: All right.

