00:43:22.500 --> 00:43:25.710
But the important thing is
there's really two ways to

00:43:25.710 --> 00:43:27.320
scale a bitmap in Android.

00:43:27.320 --> 00:43:30.950
You can use a draw bitmap and
give it a destination rect

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:33.070
that's different from your
source rect, and

00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:34.360
that will do scaling.

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:39.470
Or you can draw it to a canvas
at its original rectangle and

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:42.010
apply a scale matrix to
the entire canvas.

00:43:42.010 --> 00:43:47.610
And the problem comes when you
mix them, so when you mix the

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:48.430
two techniques.

00:43:48.430 --> 00:43:51.670
Well no, because applying the
scale matrix to the canvas is

00:43:51.670 --> 00:43:53.070
applying it to each
drawing operating.

00:43:53.070 --> 00:43:54.240
It's not a full scale.

00:43:54.240 --> 00:44:00.120
So what we were suggesting is
that you pick the canvas size

00:44:00.120 --> 00:44:04.840
that you feel is native, so
whatever you had in mind.

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:08.600
Now remember, this isn't going
to take care of aspect ratio,

00:44:08.600 --> 00:44:10.250
it's going to take
care of size.

00:44:10.250 --> 00:44:12.010
Now, for aspect ratio,
you need to

00:44:12.010 --> 00:44:17.020
make some other decisions.

00:44:17.020 --> 00:44:19.150
You may want to do a little
bit of [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:23.645
move some of your UI elements
out further or

00:44:23.645 --> 00:44:24.380
something like that.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:26.290
And the other thing that's a
little tricky is on a tablet--

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:29.550
so normally what Android does is
if you have, let's say, an

00:44:29.550 --> 00:44:33.620
xhdpi resource, and you try to
load it onto a tablet, which

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:36.530
is an MDPI device, Android's
automatically going to go

00:44:36.530 --> 00:44:38.540
[SQUISH], and it's going
to squish that down.

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:41.390
And it's going to make an MDPI
size because its goal is it's

00:44:41.390 --> 00:44:47.520
trying through to retain the
physical size of that bitmap,

00:44:47.520 --> 00:44:50.950
which for a lot of actual
non-game UI is very nice.

00:44:50.950 --> 00:44:52.970
Because what you really want
a tablet, often, is just to

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:54.970
display more information.

00:44:54.970 --> 00:44:56.680
However, there's a balance.

00:44:56.680 --> 00:44:58.100
So what you can do is
a couple of things.

00:44:58.100 --> 00:45:01.370
One is you can actually say,
when I'm on an extra-large

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:05.040
device, let's not use the DPI
that is built into it.

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:07.610
You can actually say, I'm on an
extra-large screen device,

00:45:07.610 --> 00:45:10.500
I'm going to make use of higher
resolution assets.

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:13.040
And you can actually set that
and tell the resource loader

00:45:13.040 --> 00:45:16.470
actually, go load me
the next level up.

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:18.470
The other thing you can do is,
if you're going to do that a

00:45:18.470 --> 00:45:22.760
lot, you can simply store your
resources in a no-DPI folder

00:45:22.760 --> 00:45:25.210
and then do some calculations
yourself to

00:45:25.210 --> 00:45:26.130
determine how to scale.

00:45:26.130 --> 00:45:29.260
Because actually, if you look
