00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:55.700
Your can do all of your
layouts in DIPs.

00:46:55.700 --> 00:46:58.000
The only problem with that is
obviously this thing has a

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.540
much larger amount of DIPs.

00:47:00.540 --> 00:47:02.500
And so you're going to
actually want to have

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:03.250
different resources.

00:47:03.250 --> 00:47:04.710
People don't want to have

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:07.160
HDPI-slash-extra large resources.

00:47:07.160 --> 00:47:10.240
That's actually the correct way
of having different scaled

00:47:10.240 --> 00:47:13.300
resources, is to actually have
separate bitmaps that are for

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:16.840
tablets for HDPI and for
phones for HDPI.

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:19.490
And that just gets
kind of messy.

00:47:19.490 --> 00:47:23.860
So in this case, in order to
keep the image really small,

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:25.420
in order to keep things
relatively simple, you'll

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:27.460
probably want to do a little bit
of math just to make sure

00:47:27.460 --> 00:47:30.430
you get the right size images
with the highest quality

00:47:30.430 --> 00:47:32.880
available for these
MDBI tablets.

00:47:32.880 --> 00:47:33.140
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:36.690
So let's move on
to that, then.

00:47:36.690 --> 00:47:38.270
Especially if you're
thinking in DIPs.

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:42.360
So DIPs are supposed to be
related to physical units.

00:47:42.360 --> 00:47:43.670
DAN GALPIN: And they
are, actually.

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:44.120
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:45.450
Well--

00:47:45.450 --> 00:47:45.540
yes.

00:47:45.540 --> 00:47:47.080
DAN GALPIN: They're related.

00:47:47.080 --> 00:47:49.880
They're not exactly related.

00:47:49.880 --> 00:47:53.270
IAN NI-LEWIS: So the trick here
is that a 4-inch phone

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:55.760
and a 10-inch tablet may
actually have the same number

00:47:55.760 --> 00:47:57.830
of pixels but a different
number of DIPs.

00:47:57.830 --> 00:48:00.660
So I think what we're suggesting
is that you might

00:48:00.660 --> 00:48:07.010
want to go ahead and decide on
a native dimensions in DIPs

00:48:07.010 --> 00:48:11.410
and then either expand
or contract by

00:48:11.410 --> 00:48:12.370
setting a scale factor.

00:48:12.370 --> 00:48:13.770
Now, how do you set
that scale factor?

00:48:13.770 --> 00:48:16.590
Well, you do it in the matrix
of your canvas.

00:48:16.590 --> 00:48:20.450
And you make sure that for all
of the elements that are

00:48:20.450 --> 00:48:23.680
supposed to be occupying the
same physical space in your

00:48:23.680 --> 00:48:26.500
game board, that matrix
needs to be the same.

00:48:26.500 --> 00:48:32.310
And the domino game is probably
using one matrix for

00:48:32.310 --> 00:48:35.750
drawing the triangles and
using another matrix for

00:48:35.750 --> 00:48:36.480
drawing the dots.

00:48:36.480 --> 00:48:38.280
And that's where they're
running into problems.

00:48:38.280 --> 00:48:38.520
DAN GALPIN: I think so.

00:48:38.520 --> 00:48:39.580
I think that's exactly
what's going on.

00:48:39.580 --> 00:48:43.250
I think actually, it's probably
drawing the triangles

00:48:43.250 --> 00:48:47.450
as based just purely on what's
coming on the screen.

00:48:47.450 --> 00:48:51.140
And it's probably loading the
bitmap images and making

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:52.690
assumptions about the size
of them and then

00:48:52.690 --> 00:48:54.080
trying to scale those.

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:55.700
That's my guess.

00:48:55.700 --> 00:48:59.410
We even saw on Galaxy Nexus with
that game that even going

00:48:59.410 --> 00:49:02.260
to HDMI and plugging that in
made the game unplayable.

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:04.470
So there's probably some
calculations going on that are

00:49:04.470 --> 00:49:06.990
based on the display size rather
than on the viewport

00:49:06.990 --> 00:49:08.630
size it's given as well.

00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:10.660
So there's probably a number
of different issues.

00:49:10.660 --> 00:49:13.252
You have to really make sure
that when the system tells you

00:49:13.252 --> 00:49:15.640
no, rescale your viewport, you
really have to go and redo

00:49:15.640 --> 00:49:16.630
those calculations.

00:49:16.630 --> 00:49:18.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, and that's
very important as well.

00:49:18.720 --> 00:49:21.120
So you have to remember that
you're going to be on a

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:22.570
multitude of different
devices.

00:49:22.570 --> 00:49:26.080
And this is actually where 3D
games have a real advantage

00:49:26.080 --> 00:49:31.060
because 3D games are used to
having to do viewport mapping,

00:49:31.060 --> 00:49:36.180
mapping from your 3D world, into
what we call clip space.

00:49:36.180 --> 00:49:39.260
But 2D games, a lot of times,
haven't had to deal with that

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:42.790
unless you're coming from a
background of games that were

00:49:42.790 --> 00:49:45.690
actually written to be resized
on, let's say, a desktop PC.

00:49:45.690 --> 00:49:45.920
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:48.290
And there's no reason why a game
like dominoes shouldn't

00:49:48.290 --> 00:49:50.720
be resizable and scalable.

00:49:50.720 --> 00:49:53.060
And there's a lot of ways
to attack that.

00:49:53.060 --> 00:49:56.830
So I think maybe that
helps a little bit.

00:49:56.830 --> 00:49:59.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: And if not,
drop something on

00:49:59.720 --> 00:50:01.500
Stack Overflow, and--

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:02.460
DAN GALPIN: Ian'll get
some more points.

00:50:02.460 --> 00:50:03.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: --ping
us through G+.

00:50:03.280 --> 00:50:05.160
And yeah, totally, we'll
do the work.

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:06.760
DAN GALPIN: Ian needs
some more reps.

00:50:06.760 --> 00:50:07.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, yeah.

00:50:07.020 --> 00:50:08.140
DAN GALPIN: So he'll be there.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:08.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: Big time.

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:09.860
DAN GALPIN: And so
do I, actually.

00:50:09.860 --> 00:50:12.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: Anything
else on the internet?

00:50:12.570 --> 00:50:14.800
DAN PHAM: Yeah, so this
is the last question.

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:17.300
One of our users wants to know
if we have any guidelines on

00:50:17.300 --> 00:50:20.200
dealing with performance
variety between devices

00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:22.940
because the filtering only
handles GPU and screen size.

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:24.180
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's is
the billion-dollar

00:50:24.180 --> 00:50:25.050
question, isn't it?

00:50:25.050 --> 00:50:27.810
DAN GALPIN: So yeah, actually,
it doesn't really handle GPU.

00:50:27.810 --> 00:50:30.390
It handles OpenGL ES version.

00:50:30.390 --> 00:50:32.480
And it doesn't really--

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:33.040
IAN NI-LEWIS: It handles
texture format.

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:33.590
DAN GALPIN: It handles
texture format.

00:50:33.590 --> 00:50:37.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Which is a sort
of proxy for GPU but not a

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:38.680
very good one.

00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:41.710
DAN GALPIN: So today, there's
two low-hanging fruit

00:50:41.710 --> 00:50:42.410
that you can use.

00:50:42.410 --> 00:50:44.500
One is, of course, you can say
whether or not you're actually

00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:46.400
using OpenGL ES 2.0.

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:47.950
Check that.

00:50:47.950 --> 00:50:50.480
And make sure that you're
actually filtering

00:50:50.480 --> 00:50:52.190
on OpenGL ES 2.0.

00:50:52.190 --> 00:50:53.520
The second thing you can do--

00:50:57.980 --> 00:51:01.810
this is sort of a bad option for
a lot of games if you're

00:51:01.810 --> 00:51:02.900
only using DOLVIC.

00:51:02.900 --> 00:51:05.750
But the vast majority of
performance-bound games are

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:07.590
actually using NDK.

00:51:07.590 --> 00:51:12.100
So make sure to only build an
ARMv7-A binary and/or MIPS and

00:51:12.100 --> 00:51:12.860
Intel binary.

00:51:12.860 --> 00:51:14.770
Don't target ARMv5.

00:51:14.770 --> 00:51:18.230
You'll eliminate a lot of
low-end devices that way.

00:51:18.230 --> 00:51:21.170
All right, but now you're in
the issue of, I've got this

00:51:21.170 --> 00:51:24.050
super, super, super
high-performance title that I

00:51:24.050 --> 00:51:26.910
know can only target the
top 10% of devices.

00:51:26.910 --> 00:51:30.050
Galaxy S3s, Galaxy S2s.

00:51:30.050 --> 00:51:32.700
And if you're in that position,
there's nothing you

00:51:32.700 --> 00:51:36.300
can do other than to go through
and eliminate those

00:51:36.300 --> 00:51:38.010
devices based upon our
compatibility list.

00:51:38.010 --> 00:51:40.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: And let's talk
a little bit about

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:43.290
why this is an issue.

00:51:43.290 --> 00:51:46.940
Remember that Android isn't
unique in this.

00:51:46.940 --> 00:51:48.880
I mean, in the desktop
space, this is

00:51:48.880 --> 00:51:50.470
actually pretty normal.

00:51:50.470 --> 00:51:54.250
But Android does have, actually,
a couple more GPU

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:57.770
vendors than what you'd find in
the general desktop space.

00:51:57.770 --> 00:52:01.280
And we often get the question,
well, why don't we just

00:52:01.280 --> 00:52:03.700
publish some statistics like,
what's the fill rate?

00:52:03.700 --> 00:52:04.980
Well, there's some
problems there.

00:52:04.980 --> 00:52:08.010
First off, everybody lies.

00:52:08.010 --> 00:52:12.200
And those who aren't lying are
only not lying because they're

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:13.820
bad at something else.

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:16.250
So you can talk about fill rate
and you can talk about

00:52:16.250 --> 00:52:17.600
polygon throughput.

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:19.430
You can talk about raw
vertex shader.

00:52:19.430 --> 00:52:20.870
You can talk about
memory bandwidth.

00:52:20.870 --> 00:52:26.640
But the truth is, on a GPU,
all of these things add up

00:52:26.640 --> 00:52:30.750
into something that's even only
partially the picture.

00:52:30.750 --> 00:52:34.220
Because not only do you have
different bandwidths and

00:52:34.220 --> 00:52:37.820
different fill rates and
different arithmetic unit

00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:40.720
designs, you also have
completely different

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:45.470
architectures, the main ones
being tiled or immediate mode.

00:52:45.470 --> 00:52:46.540
DAN GALPIN: And there's
actually two things.

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:49.170
There's tiled deferred mode
and then there's tiled

00:52:49.170 --> 00:52:50.035
immediate mode.

00:52:50.035 --> 00:52:51.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Which
is sort of a--

00:52:51.860 --> 00:52:52.390
yeah.

00:52:52.390 --> 00:52:55.550
DAN GALPIN: And so basically,
the question you have to ask

00:52:55.550 --> 00:52:58.990
yourself is one, how
many devices--

00:52:58.990 --> 00:53:01.920
IAN NI-LEWIS: Dude, you so
passed up an opportunity.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:02.900
DAN GALPIN: Yeah?

00:53:02.900 --> 00:53:05.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: The question you
have to ask yourself is, do

00:53:05.450 --> 00:53:06.650
you feel lucky, punk?

00:53:06.650 --> 00:53:07.450
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:53:07.450 --> 00:53:08.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, do ya?

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:09.370
DAN GALPIN: So how many
devices do you

00:53:09.370 --> 00:53:11.100
really want to hit?

00:53:11.100 --> 00:53:14.890
Today, I think you're going to
want to hit a pretty large

00:53:14.890 --> 00:53:15.870
cross-section of devices.

00:53:15.870 --> 00:53:17.620
But you might be limited
because of memory.

00:53:17.620 --> 00:53:21.550
You might be limited because
of just raw GPU power.

00:53:21.550 --> 00:53:24.510
Today on Google Play, if you're
really limited by those

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:27.570
things-- and my advice to
everyone is try to target as

00:53:27.570 --> 00:53:29.780
broad as possible.

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:33.740
If you're running a 3D game,
you're going to have a mipmap

00:53:33.740 --> 00:53:36.020
with different versions of a
texture for things that are in

00:53:36.020 --> 00:53:37.670
the distance, typically.

00:53:37.670 --> 00:53:40.110
Take advantage of that and use
different mipmap levels.

00:53:40.110 --> 00:53:41.762
IAN NI-LEWIS: Do you want
to use a MIP bias to--

00:53:41.762 --> 00:53:44.360
OK, I can see that.

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:46.740
I will say, I don't think
there's anybody that's

00:53:46.740 --> 00:53:48.520
terrible at vertex
performance.

00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:55.410
So you want to have a certain
number of vertices, and you

00:53:55.410 --> 00:53:59.210
can cut off this year's or
last year's devices.

00:53:59.210 --> 00:54:01.070
I don't actually think there's
even been that

00:54:01.070 --> 00:54:02.300
much progress in this.

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:06.480
But fill rate-wise, what's
the right thing to do?

00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:08.880
Well, Dan's got a good idea.

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:14.660
If you're bound by input,
doing a MIP bias would

00:54:14.660 --> 00:54:16.710
definitely reduce the amount of

00:54:16.710 --> 00:54:18.230
memory the GPU is consuming.

00:54:18.230 --> 00:54:22.230
It doesn't reduce the amount the
GPU is producing, which is

00:54:22.230 --> 00:54:24.600
where you would reduce your
frame buffer size.

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:28.120
DAN GALPIN: So the second thing
you can do, and a lot of

00:54:28.120 --> 00:54:30.450
developers don't do this, and I
think it's partially because

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:31.800
they don't know.

00:54:31.800 --> 00:54:32.680
It's kind of hidden.

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:34.640
But one thing that you, as a
developer, can do if you're

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:40.470
using OpenGL, is you can
actually set the size of your

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:44.455
viewport in our windowing
system, so not even in OpenGL.

00:54:44.455 --> 00:54:47.340
And we actually offer this sort
of hidden API which is

00:54:47.340 --> 00:54:51.420
inside of Surface Holder
called Set Fixed Size.

00:54:51.420 --> 00:54:54.670
And if you do that, it'll
actually automatically scale

00:54:54.670 --> 00:54:58.015
your viewport up to the
size of your window.

00:54:58.015 --> 00:55:00.030
So it's actually very,
very useful.

00:55:00.030 --> 00:55:04.490
And that's done inside of
SurfaceFlinger, and it may

00:55:04.490 --> 00:55:06.480
even be done with a
hardware composer.

00:55:06.480 --> 00:55:09.930
So for a lot of reasons, we
definitely recommend doing

00:55:09.930 --> 00:55:14.390
that, especially if your choices
are rendering to a

00:55:14.390 --> 00:55:18.500
pixel buffer or actually
rendering to using this, you

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:19.170
should definitely use this.

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:20.660
You're going to get
more performance.

00:55:20.660 --> 00:55:22.910
A lot of times when things are
really just heavily fill

00:55:22.910 --> 00:55:24.450
limited, that's what
you should do.

00:55:24.450 --> 00:55:25.690
Obviously, there's
shader effects.

00:55:25.690 --> 00:55:26.560
There's other things
you can do.

00:55:26.560 --> 00:55:28.760
But my general advice
on Android is, try

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:29.870
to make things scalable.

00:55:29.870 --> 00:55:34.240
Try not to cut off users if you
absolutely can avoid it.

00:55:34.240 --> 00:55:36.350
You want as many users as
possible to see your game.

00:55:36.350 --> 00:55:38.820
IAN NI-LEWIS: Give yourself
some knobs so you can make

00:55:38.820 --> 00:55:39.790
adjustments.

00:55:39.790 --> 00:55:43.650
Don't necessarily expose
us to the users.

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:45.690
DAN GALPIN: Well, one of my
favorite games that does this

00:55:45.690 --> 00:55:46.660
is Dead Trigger.

00:55:46.660 --> 00:55:48.520
I mean, Dead Trigger
has a slider.

00:55:48.520 --> 00:55:51.450
And with a lot of GPUs,
it'll [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:51.450 --> 00:55:53.860
It'll say, you're guaranteed
to work at the

00:55:53.860 --> 00:55:54.810
lowest quality only.

00:55:54.810 --> 00:55:57.650
But you can slide it over, and
you can, say, turn on effects.

00:55:57.650 --> 00:55:58.440
And you can see what happens.

00:55:58.440 --> 00:56:01.130
And sometimes it may just
crash the game when you

00:56:01.130 --> 00:56:03.320
actually try to run the game
with everything turned on.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:05.700
But at least the user knows,
I turned on those effects.

00:56:05.700 --> 00:56:06.820
It's crashing.

00:56:06.820 --> 00:56:08.020
That's not good for
every developer.

00:56:08.020 --> 00:56:10.070
Some developers are like, I
don't want users to ever see

00:56:10.070 --> 00:56:11.760
my title crash.

00:56:11.760 --> 00:56:14.650
I much prefer being given the
option of saying, let's try

00:56:14.650 --> 00:56:16.680
turning it up and see
what happens.

00:56:16.680 --> 00:56:18.120
And they do a whole bunch
of techniques--

00:56:18.120 --> 00:56:21.100
they actually don't even use
resolution in that slider.

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:22.500
They're simply turning
off effects.

00:56:25.455 --> 00:56:27.170
It's almost all turning
off, actually.

00:56:27.170 --> 00:56:28.466
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, remember
the things that

00:56:28.466 --> 00:56:28.610
are going to be--

00:56:28.610 --> 00:56:29.850
And texture quality.

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:32.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, texture
fetches are

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:35.570
going to be a big deal.

00:56:35.570 --> 00:56:37.280
On many GPs, especially
[INAUDIBLE]

00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:39.780
Tyler's, state changes are
going to be a big deal.

00:56:39.780 --> 00:56:41.630
On Ford renderers--

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:44.400
Tegra is the best example
of this--

00:56:44.400 --> 00:56:47.230
your geometry sorting is
going to be a big deal.

00:56:47.230 --> 00:56:49.880
DAN GALPIN: You want to take
advantage of early Z

00:56:49.880 --> 00:56:50.880
rejection on Tegra.

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:52.090
It's absolutely critical.

00:56:52.090 --> 00:56:56.220
The number of games we look at
that draw in the reverse order

00:56:56.220 --> 00:56:59.250
and end up getting really slow
performance, people are like,

00:56:59.250 --> 00:57:00.990
wow, this game is amazing
on Nexus 7.

00:57:00.990 --> 00:57:02.690
They look at the next game,
they say, well,

00:57:02.690 --> 00:57:03.980
this isn't very good.

00:57:03.980 --> 00:57:10.330
And the reason why, often,
there's kind of two things--

00:57:10.330 --> 00:57:13.450
design artwork, and also make
sure that they're doing draw

00:57:13.450 --> 00:57:16.130
order that allows for early Z to
really take best advantage

00:57:16.130 --> 00:57:17.010
of the hardware.

00:57:17.010 --> 00:57:20.010
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now, remember
that all of the GPU

00:57:20.010 --> 00:57:23.630
manufactures want games
to look great on

00:57:23.630 --> 00:57:25.470
their particular chipset.

00:57:25.470 --> 00:57:29.380
And they all have armies of
people that want to help games

00:57:29.380 --> 00:57:31.340
look better on that chipset.

00:57:31.340 --> 00:57:34.730
So if you're having specific
problems, contact Invidia,

00:57:34.730 --> 00:57:39.180
contact Qualcomm, contact
imagination Technologies.

00:57:39.180 --> 00:57:39.860
DAN GALPIN: Contact ARM.

00:57:39.860 --> 00:57:41.460
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
contact ARM--

00:57:41.460 --> 00:57:43.810
any of these.

00:57:43.810 --> 00:57:46.360
And get some help because a
lot of times, it's just a

00:57:46.360 --> 00:57:49.640
matter of rewriting a
shader or changing

00:57:49.640 --> 00:57:50.930
your draw order around.

00:57:50.930 --> 00:57:54.080
And don't forget, all of them
have really great tools for

00:57:54.080 --> 00:57:58.250
investigating what your
draw calls are doing.

00:57:58.250 --> 00:57:59.230
DAN GALPIN: I mean,
PerfHUD, the

00:57:59.230 --> 00:58:03.140
Adreno Profiler, PVRTrace--

00:58:03.140 --> 00:58:05.080
all of these tools are really,
really helpful.

00:58:05.080 --> 00:58:07.390
And the best part for me, the
exciting part, is that a lot

00:58:07.390 --> 00:58:09.230
of them now work on non-rooted
devices.

00:58:09.230 --> 00:58:12.680
